orrectOptions":[1],"correctResponses":null,"explanation":"\u003Cp\u003EThis case describes \u003Cstrong\u003Eamelia\u003C/strong\u003E, which is the complete absence of a limb from birth. It is the most severe form of limb difference and occurs due to failure of limb bud formation during early embryological development.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003E\u003Cstrong\u003EMeromelia\u003C/strong\u003E refers to a partial absence of a limb where some segments are present. \u003Cstrong\u003EPhocomelia\u003C/strong\u003E describes a condition where the proximal portions of the limb are absent or markedly hypoplastic, with relatively normal distal structures. \u003Cstrong\u003EEctromelia\u003C/strong\u003E refers to transverse limb deficiencies where the limb terminates at some point along its length. \u003Cstrong\u003EHemimelia\u003C/strong\u003E describes longitudinal deficiencies where structures along one side of the limb are absent.\u003C/p\u003E\u003Cp\u003EAmelia can occur as an isolated finding or as part of a broader syndrome. It may affect one limb (unilateral) or multiple limbs (bilateral or tetramelia).\u003C/p\u003E","optionExplanations":null,"learningPoints":["Amelia is the complete absence of a limb from birth.","Limb differences occur during embryological development, with complete absence being the most severe form."],"references":["Eghbalian F, Sharif A, Monsef AR. Amelia: A Case Report and Literature Review. Iran J Pediatr. 2015 Dec;25(6):e4114. doi: 10.5812/ijp.4114. Epub 2015 Dec 23. PMID: 26635946; PMCID: PMC4662846","Arulkumaran, S., Ledger, W., Denny, L., \u0026 Doumouchtsis, S. (Eds.). (2019). Oxford Textbook of Obstetrics and Gynaecology. Oxford University Press.","Kumar, V., Abbas, A. K., \u0026 Aster, J. C. (Eds.). (2012). Robbins basic pathology e-book. Elsevier Health Science","Singh, V. (2022). Textbook of clinical embryology, -E-Book. Elsevier Health Sciences."]},"relationships":{"itemRevision":{"data":{"type":"itemRevisions","id":"97198"}},"questi